I started dancing at 2. I started competing in dance at 7. I didn’t know it at the time, but it was my outlet. It was how I dealt with all of the chaos & toxicity around me. 

I won my first solo national dance championship at 14. After that point it was downhill, even though I had dance I needed more. I needed a therapist, I needed emotional support. I didn’t know I needed that at the time. 

Fast forward to college, I majored in dance…dance was all I knew. It was my survival lifeline. As Meryl Streep said, “take your broken heart and turn it into art”. That’s what I’ve been doing my whole life, unknowingly. 

My senior year of college I auditioned and made the dance team for the Brooklyn Nets. I danced for the NBA for 4 years. Dance started to feel yucky to me… it was something I did for me. It was how I moved emotions though me and how I released trauma and emotions. It wasn’t something I wanted to get paid to do, not anymore. It was for me. 

I started working in the NYC fitness scene and started to heal and find my voice. Then I started a podcast. Now I dance for me. I move in ways that make me feel good. I dance to process, to channel, to release.

I am an artist, a creator, a mover, a dancer. 

Try moving in ways that make you feel good, anything that puts you in a flow state. Start with minimal movements until you learn movement technique. You must know technique in order to abandon it. More on this soon. 

Til then ❤️‍🔥

#dancer #movement #mentalhealth #survival #artist

I didn’t realize just how much I *needed* dancing. I’ve needed to carve out Me Dance Time… to just dance. Pure and simple. It’s bliss 🥰

And in carving out that time, I’ve come back to my meditation, safe space, my flow state, my zone. 

Dancing is the safe place that for so many years, held my heart and soul. It allowed me to let go of all expectations and pressures, and let energy and emotions move through my body. It became the softest and most precious escape, when the rest of the world became too overwhelming, too crazy, and too much. It was the safest place in the world for me. 

And then… those shiny opportunities seduced me. I’ll admit it sounds pretty glamorous: being selected as an NBA dancer, having a NYC agent, scoring gigs like SNL, and working as a dancer for the most famous pop artists in the world. 

My life sure looked “successful” - but with all of that, came the shattering realization that dancing was “just a job” now - and that realization changed EVERYTHING. It wasn’t aligned, and it definitely wasn’t my meditation, or my special practice anymore. The fun was slowly sucked out - and I wasn’t sure if I would feel like dancing again. 

It’s been an incredible journey to dance again, to reconnect with my body again, and to heal my nervous system. I’ve re-discovered deep joy and experienced so much freedom. I’m allowing my emotions and energy to move through me, rather than staying stagnant in trauma responses - and that, is truly truly liberating. 

Dancing allows me to feel more myself, and more confident. I want to do it more, and I’m so excited about my re-established relationship with dance. 

I can’t wait to share more of my deeper connection with dance, movement, and healing ✨

#dance #healing #liberation

What a gorgeous weekend! For a task completion New Yorker who used to want everything done yesterday, it’s a relatively new experience for me to head out to a beautiful park or trail, explore with my dogs, and actually let myself have fun and be relaxed (lol, who would have thought?!).

And funnily enough, going out on these kinds of adventures has not only helped me define success, on my own terms, it’s also allowed me to feel more joy and come back to my work inspired.

Society makes us feel like we need to achieve success before we have fun. It’s all about trying to achieve accomplishment after accomplishment, and then maybe, we might be considered successful enough to deserve fun. But it feels like we’ve got things the wrong way around. Having fun and enjoying your life doesn’t need to be earned. It’s your birthright. Forever and always.

This is the most successful I’ve ever felt - from coming to the park, enjoying the moment, being in nature, laying in the sun with my dogs, and reading a book. No prerequisites are needed for this - just allowing myself to truly be present and soak it all in!

When I was 15, a sophomore in high school, the cheerleaders wrote “SL_*T” on my car.* 

Apparently, I had unknowingly made out with one of their boyfriends. My dad washed it off and told me about it, and knew that he would tell my mom. I was absolutely mortified, a feeling that was amplified by living in a traditional religious and sl_t shaming society.

I wish I could say this was the last incident that made me feel like my worth as a woman was based on how “pure” I was, or that I should be ashamed of being a $exual person. I also wish this was the last narcissistic experience I had where people took advantage of me, or where I was attacked or judged. I went through many of these experiences over and over - til I got to a point where I said… enough is enough. No more. 

I’ve done the very hard work of unpacking, processing and making peace with the fact that these kinds of toxic behaviors and actions were NOT okay. Again, I’ve made peace with it, but it was NOT okay. 

It’s taken time, as well as a gentle process of learning boundaries, accountability, and plenty of other tools to show up in relationships with integrity, kindness, and love. I’ve had to develop my self-worth, re-discover my values, and choose a different path. 

The purpose of this post isn’t to shame these people. It’s to raise awareness about societal and cultural programming around sexuality. 

- It’s not okay to engage in name-calling, of any kind.
- It’s not okay to judge a woman - and especially not for her sexual choices or her body.
- It’s not okay to attack a woman’s character. Period.

If you’ve been through these kinds of experiences - I’m with you, standing proud and loud as a rule breaker <3

PS. It can feel almost impossible to unpack and escape what is considered “normal” and “acceptable” - but it IS possible. Reach out to me if you want to chat more about unpacking this process together.

This morning I journaled, “Universe, please give me the strength to navigate the emotional immaturity in this world”

I kept journaling and as i wrote, I remembered that I was once someone who was emotionally immature. We all were. Some of us were taught as children how to healthily navigate big emotions, and some of us experienced arrested development because our childhood circumstances, environments, and experiences prevented us from developing in a healthy way, causing us to operate from the place of the wounded child who didn’t get their basic needs met, as adults. 

We all have ego but we don’t all have awareness of our ego. Awareness is where the magic happens. Awareness + vulnerability is where all judgement subsides, because when we let go of the ego’s desire to be right, we realize that there’s a chance we could be wrong. Awareness + vulnerability + empathy is the sweet spot, we have awareness of our patterns & ego, we are vulnerable enough to admit our imperfections, and we are empathetic enough to allow others to experience their journey on their timeline. We realize it’s our ego that thinks it knows better, but really, awareness of the ego allows us to sit in the pocket of the student and try to gain understanding. 

We all learn lessons at different times. We all learn different lessons, in general. We’ve all had completely different incidences shape us, upbringings, traumas. We all have unique experiences.

Emotionally mature people don’t feed their ego’s desire to be “right” or to “win”. They know how to cultivate happiness and fulfillment from within. They’ve learned to love themselves and give others the same grace they give themself. 

Life is about understanding. Become aware of your ego and simply, listen.

The day was September 7, 2021

I was trapped in an abusive relationship. I knew I had to break free of the cycle. But I was quite literally addicted to my abuser. 

That’s the thing about narcissistic abuse, they play on your empathic nature, they study you, they put on a show to get you hooked only to rip the rug out from under you when they selfishly need supply. See, “supply” means they do something intentionally to hurt their victim in order to feel better. Seeing their victim hurt makes them feel better. They don’t know how to create good feelings from within because they don’t know how to love themselves. They are deeply wounded, emotionally immature, and emotionally stunted creatures. They don’t know how to genuinely empathize because emotionally immature people lack empathy and operate out of ego. But they are con people who know how to turn on selective empathy and charm to get what they want or to come across as a decent, sometimes even incredible person. 

Like a drug addict is addicted to drugs, i was addicted to the high that came after every low.. you know, the high when they throw bare minimum breadcrumbs at you to temporarily make things right.

I was exhausted. I allowed him to drain me of every ounce of sanity and energy - like an energy vampire he’d deplete me, purposely doing things to hurt me/make me feel insecure so he could feel a little better about himself. 

But on this day, I knew I had to make a change. So I drove myself to the tattoo shop and got the date tattooed on my arm. I didn’t have all of the vocabulary and knowledge about narcissistic abuse that I have now, but i knew i had to break the abuse cycle and get out of the relationship. It was killing me. I felt my body, mind, and soul deteriorating before my eyes.  So this tattoo signifies the day I chose myself. 

I knew it would be rocky and gut wrenchingly challenging, but I also knew it was necessary. 

What makes leaving a narcissistically abusive relationship so hard is the fact that they groom you to make them the center of your world. The train you to get a high from the bare minimum. Continued in comments ⬇️

Once like yourself & your own company, your standards for outside company become higher.

The past 2 years consisted of heartbreak, a very long healing cocoon and a spiritual awakening. During this time I’ve come to love my own company. I’ve always been introverted, meaning, like 1/2 the population, I’m more comfortable focusing on my inner thoughts and ideas that processing externally and I recharge my batteries by being alone.

While some people may view being this way as sad or a negative thing, it can actually be a positive thing. Introverts likely develop due to a combination of both nature and nurture.  Trauma can cause a person to become a lot more introverted, but that’s not always the case. 

A shift towards introversion can be due to a variety of factors, such as increased wisdom and self-awareness, decreased energy for low vibe or surface level social interactions, and a greater appreciation for solitude and alone time.  This doesn’t mean we don’t socialize, it means we’re more selective about which environments we put ourselves in and for how long.

During this awakening I’ve become my own best friend. I treat myself well, I have fun with myself (and my dogs of course), I respect myself + because of this I’ve become more selective with the energy I allow in my life.  I rarely get physically sick because I’m so tuned in to my body, mind, + spirit and I listen to what they need. 

Introverts can be viewed as less confident, insecure, or shy, but these things aren’t always interrelated. I’m the most secure + confident I’ve ever been. 

Meditation, journaling, movement + connection to Source/God have been crucial to staying aligned - without these things it’s easier to stay in a state of dysregulation and to allow your ego and social pressures to dictate your behavior and decisions. 

There’s a quiet confidence and solace that comes with appreciating your own company, and it helps with attracting things that are in alignment with you rather than chasing things that are not.
